I remember this moment…

The moment when I became aware that UFC fighter’s fist (@officialdurkin) was about to make contact with my body.

From that moment till the one where I found myself on my knees was short af.

But it was what happened after the punch that I’m proud of. I stood back up, barely able to breathe and I finished the intro. 

I was able to set aside my own pain for a moment.
I really wanted to take a moment to pity myself. But I didn’t. I knew it would be better for the show. It was for the camera. And that was my job.

I was being a professional.

More days than not I get a punch in the gut in some form. What do I do? I keep moving.

That doesn’t mean I don’t stop to feel my feelings, I definitely do. But my feelings don’t dictate my behavior. I feel them. I acknowledge them. I receive the information, then keep moving with the mission.

Most people are waiting for a grand sense of purpose before they behave like a professional. 

Those people will fail. 

Those who succeed choose to behave as a professional even when the grand sense of purpose has left the room. Those people succeed because they’ve been practicing.

Words and action shape who we are… and repetition solidifies that.

Ready to become a daily professional, no matter the day?

Can you hold multiple perspectives at once?

This is something that I experienced early in my psychedelic exploration. I had heard of people talking about multiple perspectives before then but it didn’t make sense.

10 years later I know that we only experience an expansion of our perspective. What seemed like a completely different perspective was just an introduction to expansion at a rapid pace... momentarily.

Capturing that moment and bringing it into a state of consciousness that I can operate from in my daily life was the struggle. And the struggle was real.

My work then became to stabilize the expanded perspective. To create structures to support it.

And from this perspective I operate with much more MENTAL FREEDOM.

Since then I’ve used a cognitive framework that has helped me to hold that expanded view even in the face of difficult times. A framework that supports a perspective many will never know.

And those that do know it have an unfair advantage.

Increased empathy

Increased clarity on demand

And clear steps to keep progressing through the toughest of times

Sounds unfair, and I think it would be unfair to keep it all to myself. And that’s why I’m offering a free webinar tomorrow night to show you my most used framework for stabilizing an expanded perspective.

You’ll leave with more confidence in how you approach the world.

Super Elf was miserable.

I’ve spent the last 28 years optimizing myself. At first, it was because I never felt like I was enough.

My perspective on the world was stuck on just my physical body. I was interested in optimizing my mind but had 0 mentorship there. So I went 100% physical and just used my mind to dominate my body.

Maybe it was all the comic books as a kid. By the age of 13 I was convinced there was something I could do, experience, or take that would make me super human. Finally something that would make me feel like I was enough.

No matter the amount of physical training I did I never became super human. In fact, the deeper I got into training the more I was surrounded by freaks. No way I could compete with these guys.

But that didn’t stop me. From 13-31 I was LOST. All I knew to do was more.

In that time I served in the Navy (failed BUDs in the process), got my bachelor’s degree in exercise & sport science, opened a CrossFit gym, got married, bought a house, and started a podcast/YouTube channel with 10s of thousands of subscribers.

Most on the outside looking in would think that I had a good handle on things. But that was far from true.

First, I was a functioning alcoholic. I didn’t drink everyday, but by the age of 20 blacking out was a far too common occurrence. I lied to myself about the impact it was making on me.

Second, I felt completely distant from everyone around me. I was constantly concerned with how they perceived me. This caused constant stress.

Third, my marriage was a constant struggle with few highlights to keep me going. That eventually ended.

Fourth, my finances felt like a yoyo. Up and down, never constant. And I somehow seemed to spend every dime I made.

All this was happening while I was experiencing “success” by most people’s standards. I had the house, wife, business, and I was popular.

So what exactly was the problem?

I was living for other people. I was completely out of touch with myself. I hated myself.

Gain clarity with this single approach

One solution to untangle the rat’s nest of your life.

Our minds are disorganized. You can see the results of this by people’s outer experience of the world. If your life is disorganized it’s a reflection of your mind.

Get the mind organized and the outside world begins to manifest similarly. Organize the outside world and the mind begins to organize as well.

Most people put all their effort into one or the other… and rarely both at the same time.

This results in a lack of clarity and the experience of not having enough time or money. Clarity is the clearing out of the landscape so that you can see. Clean out your mind, clean out the space.

Proper organization results in having more than enough time and money to accomplish what it is you desire.

How do we do that? First, we need context. Where are you starting and where are you going? Most will define either of these well enough to be effective.

Next, we need to understand the principles behind The 3 I’s.

Isolate > Integrate > Improvise

We usually look up to people who are in the “improvise” stage of their learning. We mimic them, then wonder why we’re not getting the same results. We’re mimicking their improvisation.

Want to get into your own unique genius? Look at your life through the Big 4 Structures that have created your exact place in the world:

1. Psycho-emotional structures
2. Physical body structures
3. Relational structures
4. Environmental structures

Which one do you excel in?

Which one are you weakest?

It’s usually the one that you haven’t given the most attention as the one that has the biggest opportunity to take you toward your goal.

Apply that 3 i’s principle and focus your attention into one.

“It’s not fair”

That was the thought looping through my mind as I woke up weeping.

It was December 7th, at 4am. The morning after my brother checked into prison. This was the first time I cried about it.

Charged with a victimless crime. A charge that was used for this context for the first time. Serving 4 years. He’s a political prisoner and it’s very clear.

A wife and 2 daughters. A punishment felt through the whole family.

These are some of the things my mind attaches to as “not fair”.

Cognitively I know that “life isn’t fair”. That was a phrase ingrained in my mind by my dad. Anytime we had a complaint about the way things were we’d hear that message loud and clear.

He was right. If fairness is what I’m looking for then I can very much so spend my entire life searching for it. And I would never find it. Because fairness is in the eye of the beholder. It’s subjective.

But that doesn’t mean that our mind won’t waste our time and energy looking for it.

So what’s underneath the “it’s not fair” narrative?

Sadness. I’m sad about the situation. And before I could feel the sadness I felt a lot of anger. I won’t even tell you the visions that ran through my head about the people who are responsible for locking my brother away.

But underneath anger is usually sadness. So as I laid there for a good half hour letting out a good cry I got to feel all the sadness. I let it all move through me. I then drifted back to sleep and woke up feeling much lighter.

I was able to move into acceptance. As much as I wanted to get there without feeling all the feels, that's exactly what I needed.

So today I’m driving to Tennessee with my fiance to see the family. I’ll see brothers and sisters, nieces and nephews. I’ll also get some time with my two nieces who’s dad is in prison. It’s been a little over 3 weeks. I want to make sure there’s some healthy male presence in their life while dad is gone.

So this is Christmas for me. 8 nephews and nieces, 3 siblings, and my mom to visit. There will be smiles and holiday cheer, and I’m sure there will be moments where we acknowledge the person who’s missing from the room.

3 things we cannot outsource if we want freedom
No one is better than you at taking care of you… 

As much as anyone may try. Giving all they have for you still won’t bring you to health and fulfillment.

We live in a society of outsourcing. Capitalism is a great system of exchange which has allowed us to each specialize deeply into our work. Outsourcing everything outside of our specialty to another specialist.

It’s amazing. Capitalism has helped bring more people out of poverty than any other economic system. But the mentality that can come along with it is dangerous.

There are 3 things we cannot outsource. That is our health, our wealth, and our relationships. No matter the amount of money and resources are given to you, those 3 things cannot be outsourced. And no, having a lot of money does not equal wealth. We can define that later.

So in a culture where we’re constantly outsourcing everything I can see how we get confused about what we hire out versus what we need to become responsible for ourselves.

Survive & thrive in the age of AI

Artificial Intelligence is here. In fact OpenAI’s Chat GPT was the most advanced toy we played with on Christmas Day.

And it’s very clear that it’s going to change the world at a pace you can’t even imagine.

There are 2 camps of people anytime new technology emerges. The first comprising the majority of the population. These people are used by the tech. A simple example is social media. Most people are consumed with it. They spend a lot of time and energy consuming the content.

The 2nd camp are those who leverage the technology to create value for others. These are the producers. The winners.

If you’re waiting for the right tech to come along in order to fall in the 2nd camp you’ll be waiting forever. It’s not about the tech. It’s about how you already use the tech that’s available to you.

Most people will be lost in the next few years as jobs disappear and new skills will be necessary to learn in order to “keep busy”.

In the book “The Last Safe Investment”, Bryan Franklin and Michael Ellsberg outline the 4 categories of labor:

Physical
Technical
Creative
Interpersonal

Categories are listed in order of market value. Physical labor typically being the lowest paid jobs (NBA excluded), whereas Interpersonal labor is typically the highest paying (sales, executives, etc.).

Not only is working in the lower categories guaranteed to make you less money, but those are the first jobs to go in an age of AI. Robot technology is about to get crazy. Physical and technical labor is going away.

Example: truck drivers are about to be replaced with self driving Tesla freight. There are over 3.5 million truck drivers in the US. What happens to all those drivers as companies realize that it’s safer and more cost effective to let the AI driven robots do the job?

Most people are just going to complain about it. They’ll wait on their Universal Basic Income (UBI) checks which will enable them to continue to be consumers without producing much of anything of value to others.

The problem with single focus

Everyone knows the difference between software and hardware.

Take your phone for instance. The phone itself with the processor, screen, and all the other physical components that make it up are the hardware.

The software is the operating system and apps. All of which is made up of code. The code lives in the background and is mostly invisible to the user. The only thing the user sees is the UI (user interface). Just a snippet of what makes up the software.

Over time the software that’s been developed has driven greater demands for the hardware. More power is necessary to run more sophisticated applications. That's why your phone slows down every couple years and you’re driven to buy the latest and greatest hardware.

I like to think about us as humans in this way. We have our thoughts and emotions that are the software and the hardware is the physical body.

There’s a major difference between us and the computers and phones though. Our software causes the hardware to upgrade itself. And the hardware gives space for the software to develop itself.

We can think about it only in terms of upgrades but the same goes for bugs and viruses/trauma. The software can quite easily and quickly downgrade the hardware. And the hardware if damaged will cause an automatic limitation of the software.

The beautiful thing is, you are in control of the whole system. You can cultivate better software and hardware.

Usually people focus on one or the other. Giving them limited results. But what if we were to upgrade both, simultaneously?

What if we were to intentionally upgrade the software and then intentionally upgrade the hardware to meet the new requirements?

How much faster would the upgrades come online?

I slept in the tiny crawl space above the office in CrossFit Memphis for 8 months

I believed that the “if you build it, they will come” story was true...

What a hoax that was

We were the FIRST EVER CrossFit Gym in Memphis. I had the certifications I thought I needed.

It’s a simple “supply and demand” equation, right?
...it wasn’t

Turns out people had no idea what CrossFit was and simply because I loved it didn’t mean they would too. It also turns out no-one cared about those certifications or deep knowledge I had either.

Would you believe that in order to run a successful coaching business you’ve got to have the business stuff figured out too?

Those certifications weren't enough.

Young Mike was ignorant and egotistical. I wish I’d known this back then when I was scrounging through the couch looking for money to buy food and gas.

But hey, that challenge is what forced me to get uncomfortable and realize something had to change.

I spent my last $7k on a business event that saw the trajectory of my life change…
The gym “blew up”. I began running the business like an actual business and we began attracting people, bringing them in as clients and retaining them for years

Shrugged began to take off. Especially when we offered a specific result in a specific amount of time. As it turns out, people love that kind of thing and it’s a simple marketing gem.

Right now, if you’re the kind of coach who’s stuck in this “I’ve built it, where the hell are they” mentality and you’re struggling to bring new clients through the door and put food on the table and gas in the car - here’s the best thing you can do for yourself…

“Does somebody have a case of the Mondays?”

I hope you get the movie reference. If not, go watch “Office Space” right now!!!

As funny as the movie is, it’s deeply philosophical.

Peter Gibbons hits rock bottom. He thinks about quitting but instead just starts behaving in a way that gets him fired.

He intentionally shows up late, doesn’t give a flying duck about what his manager and colleagues think, and simply takes days off to do what he feels like doing.

He starts to play. Those around him are confused. 

The result? 

He shockingly receives a promotion in the midst of a company downsizing. Everyone at work is living in constant fear and he simply doesn’t care.

In the course of the movie he finds his simple passion and begins to live his best life. The universe rewards him.

Have you experienced this before?

I have. And it is awesome.

The more I play, the more people are attracted to me. The more success I get to enjoy.

And I notice the same thing with others.

Is Elon Musk playing? Is Twitter his toy? Are people confused about his behavior and about why he keeps getting results?

Absolutely! It’s because he’s playing.

In a world of serious, the playful entrepreneur wins the game.

Everyone else doesn’t have to have fun so you can. You get to have fun with and be successful no matter what the rest of the world is doing.

Make the things that seem hard play. Set a clock for 30 minutes and play with that part of your business that you’ve been taking so serious.

AI and the Human Spirit: A Path to Liberation or Loss?

It’s up to you.

I haven’t posted much or sent any emails to my list in a few weeks. It’s because I’ve been in the AI rabbit hole.

Flashbacks to my teenage years have been emerging. AOL launched its chat rooms, and html tools began to emerge allowing me to build websites. 

Everyday I couldn’t wait to get to the computer. I was curious… and that experience of witnessing another major world shifting innovation is here again.

As news and innovations are pouring in by the day social media is displaying the fears of those who see jobs disappearing. And it’s true.

In a leaked paper by Goldman Sachs a few weeks ago they reported an estimate of over 300 million jobs to be replaced by AI, while also seeing a global increase in GDP by 7% or more (that’s the good news).

But the truth is, the job loss is temporary. People pivot. We adapt to the environment. 

The question is, how long will it take you to adapt? That dictates the amount of suffering you will experience.

An increase in GDP is a way of measuring increases in wealth over an entire nation or the world in this case. Will it be evenly distributed? No. It always rewards the innovators and early adopters first… and those who cling to the past, as if it’s their right to keep, will watch themselves fall into the abyss of fear until someone who has been innovating and adopting exactly how to use it.

The cycles of innovation will always exist. How will you position yourself?

It’s been said “You should sit in meditation for 20 minutes a day. Unless you’re too busy, then you should sit for an hour”

“Too Busy” is a mindset. It sets the dial of your mind to to one setting… One belief.

The belief that you cannot do anything more than you’re already doing. 

Instead, try this setting on for a try, turn the dial to “I have priorities”.

Take a few minutes to identify your values, then list them in order of importance.

What do you value most?

Can you commit to 30 minutes a day for the next 90 days to get absolutely clear on your values, mission and vision?

Set your priorities and create a life where you’re actually effective instead of staying stuck in the never-ending loop of “Too Busy”.

I recognize you. I acknowledge you. I thank you.

What have I done? 

If you’ve experienced the agony of wondering if you’re making the right decision this is for you.

Many people that have come to me over the years have asked me about purpose. I guess I had somehow given off the signal that I had found mine.

But the truth is, that purpose has changed several times over the years and I continue to refine what it is I’m here to do.

As much as many people would prefer that it simply stay the same their entire lives, that’s just not how the universe works. I think we all know that.

I see that people are looking for a reason to live. Something to commit themselves to. To end each day of work with a feeling of satisfaction. A certainty that what they’re doing and how they’re living is correct.

And what keeps someone from living inside of their purpose is fear.

Fear that they didn’t pick the right thing. That it’s not actually going to create satisfaction. That to do what they want to do won’t pay the bills which will also turn into dissatisfaction.

I get it. We want certainty. We were trained to avoid mistakes. We were taught to do it right the first time or else we were punished.

But that’s not how life works. We have to fail to know. Be willing to quit once we find out that we don’t actually love that job.

A frame I’ve held for many years is that failure is feedback, which allows us to feedforward. So fail fast, and fail often.

When I run into people who are living their best lives I commonly find a spotted past. That is, they tried all sorts of things that didn’t even seem related… then one day BAM!, they find it.

It wasn’t some master plan or a step-by-step roadmap a mentor handed them. It was a magnificent amount of trial and error.

So purpose isn’t something we can even put words to. It’s an experience and we know when we’re having it. It’s a feeling we have deep inside when we’re in aligned action.

You can look back and remember those moments. Some of them are grand. Some of them are small.

A small one I have is a morning I spent in the San Diego bay on a paddleboard picking trash out of the ocean.

What I learned from being a monk for 10 days

First, I’ll tell you about what I actually mean by “being a monk”.

On November 22nd, I embarked on a 10-day Vipassana retreat in Texas, surrendering my phone, wallet, and all distractions to immerse in meditation and self-discovery.

No reading or writing materials either.

This wasn’t your beach meditation retreat with yoga and Buddha bowls. Everything was bland. Sights, smells, and sounds. Very little going on.

Meditation? 10.5 hours a day. Complete silence.

Thoughts? No mantras, no images to hold in the mind. Simply sensations. Thought slowed down and at  times subsided completely.

No breathwork, no yoga.

We ate, we slept, we had 100 yard path we could walk, and our 10×10 dorm room with a twin size bed, toilet, sink and shower was the scene.

The first 3 days our job was to reach Samhadi, a complete concentration of the mind. You know that you’ve gotten there when everything but the single point that you’re focused on drops away.

The only time I’ve experienced anything like it is when I was participating in flow state activities like snowboarding, or by using psychedelics. Except this time I didn’t need an external variable to force my mind into this position.

Now that’s where most meditation techniques end, but that was just the beginning for us.

30 hours of concentrating the mind left me feeling superhuman. No nootropics had ever taken me to this place. This is work that must be achieved simply through practice.

Next came 7 days of practicing the Vipassana technique. A systematic approaching to scanning the body to experience every sensation in every nook and cranny. That’s 70 hours of observing sensation.

Sitting completely still for an hour at a time no matter how uncomfortable I became. I noticed the pain, I noticed the tingles, the temperature on my skin. All of it.

The goal, to remain equanimous with all of it. To break the patterns of aversion and craving.
